---
import BaseHead from "../components/BaseHead.astro";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
import { SITE_TITLE, SITE_DESCRIPTION } from "../consts";
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION} />
    <style>
      /* Global Styles */
      body {
        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
        background-color: #f4f4f4;
        color: #333;
        line-height: 1.6;
      }

      ul,
      ol {
        list-style: none;
      }

      /* Container Styles */
      .container {
        max-width: 1200px;
        margin: 0 auto;
        padding: 20px;
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
        gap: 40px;
      }

      /* Full Row Styles */
      .full-row {
        background: #fff;
        border-radius: 8px;
        box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        padding: 30px;
        text-align: center;
        margin-bottom: 20px;
      }

      /* Header Styles */
      .header {
        background-color: #333;
        color: #fff;
        text-align: center;
        padding: 20px 0;
        margin-bottom: 20px;
      }

      /* Section Styles */
      .section {
        background: #fff;
        border-radius: 8px;
        box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
        padding: 20px;
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
        gap: 10px;
      }

      .section h2 {
        margin-top: 0;
        color: #333;
      }

      .section p,
      .section ul,
      .section ol {
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
      }

      /* Responsive Grid Layout */
      @media (min-width: 768px) {
        .container {
          display: grid;
          grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
          gap: 20px;
        }

        .section {
          padding: 30px;
          margin-bottom: 20px;
        }

        .full-row {
          margin-bottom: 20px;
          grid-column: span 2;
        }
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <Header />

    <main class="container">
      <!-- New Section: Welcome Message -->
      <section class="full-row welcome-section">
        <h2>Welcome to Beer Ratings</h2>
        <p>
          Discover and compare ratings of various beers, explore different
          styles, and find the best glassware for your favorite brews. Whether
          you're an aficionado or just getting started, this site is your guide
          to the world of beer.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section: Beer Styles -->
      <section class="section beer-styles">
        <h2>Beer Styles</h2>
        <p>
          Beer styles range from light lagers to dark stouts, each with unique
          characteristics. Here are some common beer styles:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Lager:</strong> A light, crisp, and refreshing beer. Ideal for
            hot weather.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Ale:</strong> Known for its fruity and spicy flavors. Ales are
            usually fuller-bodied than lagers.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Stout:</strong> A dark, rich beer with flavors of coffee, chocolate,
            and roasted malt.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>IPA (India Pale Ale):</strong> A hoppy beer style known for its
            strong, bitter flavor and floral aroma.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Wheat Beer:</strong> A light and cloudy beer with a smooth, slightly
            sweet taste.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Sour Beer:</strong> A tart and tangy beer with a unique acidic
            flavor profile.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Section: Taste Profiles -->
      <section class="section taste-profiles">
        <h2>Taste Profiles of Beers</h2>
        <p>
          Understanding the taste profile of a beer can enhance your tasting
          experience. Here are some common taste descriptors:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Sweet:</strong> Rich malt flavors, often found in stouts and
            porters.
          </li>
          <li><strong>Bitter:</strong> Hoppy and resinous, typical of IPAs.</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Sour:</strong> Tart and acidic, characteristic of sour beers.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Fruity:</strong> Notes of citrus, berries, or tropical fruits,
            often found in wheat beers and IPAs.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Spicy:</strong> Clove, pepper, and other spice notes, common
            in Belgian ales.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Section: Beer Glassware -->
      <section class="section beer-glassware">
        <h2>Beer Glassware</h2>
        <p>
          The right glass can enhance the aroma and flavor of your beer. Here
          are some common types of beer glassware:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Pint Glass:</strong> A versatile glass suitable for most beer
            styles.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Snifter:</strong> Ideal for strong ales and stouts, allowing
            you to swirl the beer and release its aromas.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Weizen Glass:</strong> Tall and curved, perfect for wheat beers.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Pilsner Glass:</strong> A tall, slender glass that showcases
            the color and carbonation of lagers and pilsners.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Goblet:</strong> Wide-mouthed glass ideal for Belgian ales and
            other rich beers.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Section: Tasting and Evaluating Beer -->
      <section class="section tasting">
        <h2>Tasting and Evaluating Beer</h2>
        <p>
          Enhance your beer tasting experience with tips on how to properly
          taste and evaluate different types of beer.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Appearance:</strong> Observe the beer's color, clarity, and foam.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Aroma:</strong> Swirl the beer gently and take a deep sniff.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Taste:</strong> Take a small sip and consider the balance of
            flavors.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Mouthfeel:</strong> Pay attention to the texture and body of
            the beer.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Finish:</strong> Notice the aftertaste and how long the flavors
            linger.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <!-- Section: Homebrewing Basics -->
      <section class="section homebrewing">
        <h2>Homebrewing Basics</h2>
        <p>
          Learn the essentials of homebrewing and start brewing your own
          delicious beer at home.
        </p>
        <h3>Essential Equipment</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Brewing Kettle:</strong> A large pot for boiling wort.
          </li>
          <li><strong>Fermenter:</strong> A container for fermentation.</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Airlock and Bung:</strong> Used to seal the fermenter.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Thermometer:</strong> For accurate temperature control.
          </li>
          <li><strong>Sanitizer:</strong> To prevent contamination.</li>
          <li><strong>Bottling Equipment:</strong> For packaging your beer.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Section: Health and Beer -->
      <section class="section health">
        <h2>Health and Beer</h2>
        <p>
          Explore the health benefits and risks associated with beer
          consumption. Learn how to enjoy beer responsibly as part of a balanced
          lifestyle.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Moderate Consumption:</strong> Benefits of drinking beer in moderation.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Antioxidants:</strong> The health benefits of antioxidants found
            in beer.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Risks of Overconsumption:</strong> Health risks associated with
            excessive drinking.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Section: Beer Myths and Facts -->
      <section class="section myths">
        <h2>Beer Myths and Facts</h2>
        <p>
          Debunk common myths about beer and learn the real facts behind popular
          misconceptions.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Myth:</strong> Dark beers are stronger than light beers.
            <br />
            <strong>Fact:</strong> Color does not indicate strength.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Myth:</strong> Beer should always be served ice-cold.
            <br />
            <strong>Fact:</strong> Some beers are best served at warmer temperatures.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Myth:</strong> Beer causes "beer belly."
            <br />
            <strong>Fact:</strong> Weight gain is due to excess calories, not beer
            itself.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Section: Beer and the Environment -->
      <section class="section environment">
        <h2>Beer and the Environment</h2>
        <p>
          Understand the environmental impact of beer production and learn how
          breweries are adopting sustainable practices.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Water Usage:</strong> Beer production is water-intensive.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Energy Consumption:</strong> Brewing requires significant energy.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Recycling and Waste Management:</strong> Sustainable practices
            in breweries.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- New Section: About This Site -->
      <section class="full-row about-section">
        <h2>About This Site</h2>
        <p>
          This website is designed to help beer enthusiasts explore and compare
          different beers based on ratings. Whether you're looking for the
          top-rated beers or learning more about various beer styles and
          glassware, this site is your ultimate beer companion.
        </p>
      </section>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
